      '<div id="content"><h1><span style="margin-right: 5px; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">Sayaka</span><span style="margin-right: 5px; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">Ganz</span><span style="margin-right: 5px; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">FORT</span><span style="margin-right: 5px; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">WAYNE,</span><span style="margin-right: 5px; font-size: 16px; font-weight: bold;">IN</span></h1><div class="post_content_full"><p style="text-align: justify;"><img src="/images/ypon/sayakaganz_234432432.jpg" /></p><p style="text-align: justify;"><img src="/images/ypon/sayakaganz_4353345345.jpg" /></p><p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p><p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>About Sayaka:</strong><br /><span>Sayaka Ganz was born in Yokohama and identifies a strong Japanese influence in her work, even though she grew up in several different countries. During her BFA studies at Indiana University Bloomington she explored various media, from ceramics to printmaking, before determining sculpture and welding as her expressive vehicles of choice.</span><br /><span>A fascination with animals in movement permeates in this collection: “When you look at the piece from the distance you see the form of the horse galloping, but when you get up close you start to see the individual objects that were used”, she writes.</span><br /><span>Sayaka lives and works in Indiana, teaching drawing and design at IU-Purdue University Fort Wayne in Indiana and making welded steel figures, of humans and other animals.</span><br /><br /><span>Source: igoogle.com</span></p></div><div class="post_info_full left">Ангилал:<a href="/sidebar/temdeglel">ТЭМДЭГЛЭЛ</a></div><div class="post_info_full right">2012.04.03</div><div class="clear"></div></div>',

